feedback_text:
My experience with the Erasmus+ office in Cyprus is excellent. It is obvious that people working in the service want to help carry out the project as well as possible in order to maximise its impact. The procedures are likely to be simplified in terms of individual elements (such as in cases where elements of a project need to be changed), while in relation to the individual elements that the evaluation will assess, I can note the following:

• the enhanced inclusion and diversity measures of the programme; 
The programme enhances diversity by allowing non-discriminatory and bottom-up actions. 

• the Programme’s contribution to mainstreaming climate actions; 
The programme includes climate actions, both horizontal (such as green travelling) and vertical (such as climate-focused financing). 

• simplifications such as the introduction of the lump sum approach in cooperation projects; 
I believe that the introduction of the lump sum approach to cooperation projects should be extended, as this would allow more participants to participate in actions such as co-participative or educational activities, and to spread the impact of the programme further. 

• the participation of the outermost regions and overseas countries or territories in the Programme; 
The participation of outermost regions seems to be supported by the programme, so that the participation of overseas regions would be better facilitated, as often the participation of groups/scientists from these regions can give key elements to a project. 

• the progress of institutions pursuing an objective of European interest and funded under the Jean Monnet actions in order to achieve the objectives of the programme.  
DG/DK.

For the period 2021-2027, it would be important to take into account a reorientation/reorganisation of national budgets in the middle of the implementation of the programme in order to increase implementation at the end of the period. National Agencies should therefore create budget lines for mobility covering:
• Budget breakdown of mobility by education/training mode (e.g. Apprenticeships in Vocational Education — Schools, Vocational Education — others, Adult Education and Training; Higher education, etc.);
• Allocation taking into account the pupils/trainees enrolled in the various modalities in the last 5 years; 
• Incorporate indicators of annual balance/reorientation according to the various budgetary arrangements and implementation of the previous year.

The University of Porto has been one of the Portuguese Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) most active in the context of Erasmus + and recognises opportunities for excellence for its academic community and for itself as an organisation. However, I would like to highlight some aspects in the context of the management and implementation of the International Credit Mobility Action that deserve analysis and possible adjustment in order to maximise the impact of projects and simplify their management and implementation:
A. We note that, in situations of force majeure duly validated by the NA, participants should not be asked to return the grant (or part thereof), for example in cases of academic inadaptation leading to suspension of the grant and return to home;
b. The bureaucratic process involving the Interinstitutional Agreements (IIA) should be simplified, not requiring signature by the legal representative of the institution and only one general agreement (MoU) signed at the launch of the project; 
c. The final report of the participants presents subjective or potentially misinterpreted issues, such as those related to the “European sentiment” as it is a global/global project and we therefore suggest its removal;
D. The final report of the KA1 projects should be reduced, there are many questions of interpretation of statistical data that should be used to comment only in cases where low percentages are identified, and there are many issues that are repetitive from year to year, so a more focused report on the financial part and only a short narrative description of activities, dissemination and impact would be useful;
e. A detailed guide to procedures, drawn up by the European Commission or the National Agency, for management and implementation would be most useful in supporting the coordinating institutions of these projects; 
f. It would be important for the European Commission to engage in joint work with the European Union Delegations, promoting greater knowledge of the Programme and its objectives through meetings and clarifications at the highest level with the national authorities, so as to make it possible to speed up the issuing of visas to ICM fellows.

The Detergents Regulation should remain a stand-alone Regulation. It is a very well-established sector specific scheme for detergents, well implemented by companies and accepted by the authorities. We therefore prefer an amendment or minor amendments to the Detergents Regulation and no merger with other legal matters. Any elements of the chemicals strategy for sustainability should be integrated, if necessary, as part of such a revision.

We see room for improvement in the following aspects:
— optimisation of the interface between the medical fiche and CLP, Annex VIII (PCN);
— optimisation of the interface with biocidal product law in the labelling of preservatives; 
— Simplifying labelling and increasing the use of digital solutions.

The University of Porto has been one of the Portuguese Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) most active in the context of Erasmus + and recognises opportunities for excellence for its academic community and for itself as an organisation. However, I would like to highlight some aspects in the context of financing the International Credit Mobility Action that deserve analysis and possible adjustment in order to maximise the impact of projects and simplify their management and implementation:

A. whereas insurance is compulsory for participants, the OS should include an amount for insurance, as was the case in the past under the Erasmus Mundus Action 2 programme;
b. We welcome the increase in the allocation of OS that brought this programme, since the previous figure was clearly insufficient for the needs identified (full payment of language course, integration activities, insurance, issuing of visas, stop-overs for visa applications, etc.), often forcing HEIs to allocate their own resources with great difficulty in order to ensure the quality of project implementation. We believe that with an increase in this heading, there is room for improvement in the quality of projects. In particular, an increase in the OS budget could make it possible to hold at least one plenary meeting with all the partner institutions of the project. This would be a very important opportunity for capacity building as it would facilitate the presentation of procedures, the applicable rules and the organisation of the details associated with the implementation of the project. At present, HEIs participating in several KA107 projects have very different procedures and different guidelines in different coordination, leading to confusion in the partner HEIs. Based on our previous experience, we believe that the ideal would be to organise a kick-off meeting at the beginning of the project and a final meeting to consolidate the results and implement their dissemination strategy;
c. We consider that there should be a OS defined by the European Commission for LCI project partners — a lump sum similar to the previous Erasmus Mundus Action 2 programme — as this is one of the issues that causes the greatest divergence with partners in the Programme partner countries;
D. Travel bands have considerable lags in real market values: e.g. travel band between Portugal and Algeria or Morocco (very small linear distance), the value of which is not compatible with the provision of flights, preventing the purchase of air travel within the maximum band values. We think it is important to reflect on the criterion for defining the travel value by separating it from the distance band between the two HEIs.
e. There should be a visa heading (a unit value at least for IN students);
f. At the level of budgetary management, we believe that it would be extremely beneficial to have full flexibility in the implementation of the envelopes, rather than by country, in order to facilitate the implementation of 100 % of the funding and, above all, to meet the needs identified in the meantime throughout the implementation of the project. Financial management based on respect for values per country is highly rigid and becomes extremely complex for many HEIs; 
g. The redistribution of the remaining budget between the national HEIs should be done by the National Agency no later than 6 months before the end of the project, in order to avoid unnecessary returns and to allow (for HEIs with capacity) the timely implementation of the remaining funds, not only by allocating new grants but also by allowing extensions of mobilities, which requires more advance notice.

The University of Porto recognises Erasmus + opportunities for excellence for its academic community and for itself as an organisation. However, I would like to highlight some aspects in the context of the management and implementation of Credit Mobility that deserve analysis and possible adjustment, as well as to give some suggestions:
A. Participants from the various typologies report in their individual reports that they find it difficult to carry out mobility with such a small grant. In addition to a general revision/update of the grant table, we consider that, in the case of students and recent graduates, consideration could be given to the option of allocating a travel support envelope, as is the case at the LCI and even in the KA131 itself for staff and also for students and recent graduates from the outermost regions, thus promoting greater equality of treatment between the different beneficiaries and increasing the participation of more disadvantaged backgrounds students. As a result of the concern about the inclusion priority, UPorto has approved the application of the project KA2 Erasmus mus4All (2021-1-PT01-KA220-HED-000023302), building precisely on the difficulties and financial shortcomings expressed by the participants that have been registered over the years;
B. considers that there should be greater flexibility in relation to financial distribution by allowing, for example, the payment of days to the ‘0 grant’ after the end of the mobility, in the event that there is still funding due to final date hits or last-minute withdrawals. This would allow for a more efficient management of funding, also contributing to increased satisfaction from the fellows;
C. we suggest creating a top-up for the automatic allocation of a percentage stipulated solely on the basis of the SEN, by category, in the light of the application documents proving this need. This would allow the National Agency (NA) to manage more effectively the amount allocated to this type of complementary support. At present, from the point of view of bureaucratic visa, SEN fellows are disadvantaged in relation to, for example, social action fellows;
D. Erasmus + mobility participants for studies or traineeships have increasingly requested mobility of longer duration, so that there should also be an adjustment in relation to the minimum periods that are funded by the NA/EC;
E. in order to help mitigate the challenges caused by housing pressure across Europe, a hosting platform linked to the Erasmus + programme, a European database, could be set up, with the various offers available in each city and where registered offers would be permanently available to host mobility students. Students would even be able to assess their stay and provide feedback on the accommodation in which they were staying, and thus there would be an aggregated tool where students could consult offers according to their destination and, through evaluations, already find additional information on, for example, the quality of the accommodation;
f. It would be very beneficial to have an information aggregator of the different projects coordinated by each HEI in order to “extract” in detail from MT + (or WB) the number of fellows and the funding granted, per academic year and project duration (e.g. all projects approved in 2019);
G. we also suggest creating a single European traineeship platform, or strengthening the erasmusintern.org platform, as a major “E + traineeship offer repository” in the EU to allow for a more dynamic dissemination of SMP opportunities. Applicants have great difficulties in getting a traineeship in the EU, as the market is very large.
